International Criminal Law recognizes the theory of state responsibility and individual responsibility for international crimes committed. However, states often have reasons to avoid the obligation to prosecute perpetrators in crimes involving states, creating a climate of impunity.

Please read the review below for a further explanation.

This article is an English translation ofTanggung Jawab Negara dan Individu atas Kejahatan Internasional, written byRenata Christha Auli, S.H.,and was published on 3 August 2022.

Before answering your main question, we should understand the different international crime types.

In International Criminal Law, there are four crimes that are referred to as truly/core international crimes. Truly international crimes are then termed as crimes against the international community as a whole. Meanwhile, other international crimes are known as crimes against states.]

The following are the types of truly international crimes.

War crimes must meet the following elements:]

These crimes require the victims to be civilians regardless of their nationality and whether or not they are considered enemies. These crimes must be committed as part of a widespread or systematic attack.]

Genocide is the crime of denying the existence of a group of people for racial, ethnical, religious, or national reasons. The international element of this crime is the specific intent of the perpetrator to destroy these 4 things, as stipulated inArticle 21948 Genocide Convention. Criminal responsibility is not only imposed on individuals, but also the state because it is categorized as a very serious wrongful act of state.]

Also read:One Man's War

Article 1 ofUNGA Res. No. 3314/1974explains that"aggression is the use of armed force by a state against the sovereignty, territorial integrity or political independence of another state...". Based on this resolution, the elements of aggression as an international crime must show a widespread or massive character. Individuals who commit aggression must fulfill the subjective element in the form of intent. This means that the perpetrator must intend to plan, participate in, or commit aggression and be aware of the consequences. In addition, it must be proven that there is a specific intent, namely the desire to gain territory or economic benefits or deliberately interfere in the internal affairs of the victim state.]

It should be noted that the four international crimes are regulated inArticle 51998 Rome Statute, which states that the International Criminal Court ("ICC") has material jurisdiction over the crimes of genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes, and aggression.

Also read:International Criminal Court, Here Are Its Definition and Jurisdictions

In addition to core international crimes, here are other types of international crimes:

Torture is considered an international crime because it requires the involvement of a state to fulfill the elements of this crime. Universal jurisdiction applies to this crime.]A full explanation of the definition of torture can be found inArticle 11984 Convention Against Torture.

Basically, there is no universal definition for terrorism, but the practice of international law shows that there are similar elements of terrorism such as the act is a criminal offense under national law, has a transnational character whose impact does not involve only one state, is carried out with the aim of forcing states or international organizations to do or not do something, spreading terror, and motivated by ideological reasons.]

Meanwhile,Bassiouniclassifies 22 international crimes, namely aggression, war crimes, unlawful use of weapons, crimes against humanity, genocide, racial discrimination and apartheid, slavery and related crimes, torture, Unlawful human experimentation, piracy, aircraft hijacking, threat and use of force against internationally protected persons, taking of civilian hostages, drug offenses, international traffic in obscene publications, destruction and/or theft of national treasures, environmental protection, theft of nuclear materials, unlawful use of the mails, interference with submarine cables, falsification and counterfeiting, dan bribery of foreign public officials.]

The concept of core international crimes has greatly influenced the theory of state responsibility.]In International Criminal Law, there is state responsibility for violations ofjus cogensand violations oferga omnesobligations. But first, let us understand the definitions ofjus cogensanderga omnes.

Based onArticle 531969 VCLT, the elements that must be met in ajus cogensnorm are that it is accepted and recognized by the entire international community, superior (cannot be reduced and changed by norms that do not have the same character), and international agreements that violate this norm must be null and void.]Meanwhile,erga omnesobligations are obligations between the subject of international law and the international community as a whole.]

In relation to truly international crimes, these crimes meet the standard of eligibility to be criminalized internationally, hence thejus cogenscharacter of the crimes is fulfilled.]It is a violation oferga omnesobligations.]

Article 48 section (1) letter bARSIWAstates that:

Any State other than an injured State is entitled to invoke the responsibility of another State in accordance with paragraph 2 if:

(b) the obligation breached is owed to the international community as a whole.

This means that the non-injured state has the authority to sue other states that violate obligations of the international community as a whole (erga omnes).]

Then,Article 41 ARSIWAregulates the legal consequences of serious violations ofjus cogensnorms, as follows:

Although the ARSIWA does not explicitly link tojus cogens, the fact that the articles in the ARSIWA allow "any state" to prosecute the violating state, gives an understanding that the nature of the violation must be serious and the norm violated must be a universal norm protected by all states. Thus, this fulfills the criteria of ajus cogensnorm.]

Individual criminal responsibility in International Criminal Law means that any person who commits an act that is regulated as a crime under international law must be responsible and therefore liable to punishment.]

In crimes involving states, states often have reasons to avoid the obligation to prosecute perpetrators. For example, non-intervention, amnesty, official immunity, and the inadequacy of national laws to prosecute perpetrators. As a result, if left unchecked, these extraordinary crimes will create a climate of impunity. This has prompted the international community to create international criminal tribunals to prosecute such crimes directly.]

Some examples of Ad Hoc international criminal tribunals are the International Military Tribunal Nürnberg, the International Military Tribunal for the Far East, the International Criminal Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia (ICTY), and the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR). In addition to Ad Hoc international criminal tribunals, there is the ICC which is permanent and has the power to exercise its jurisdiction over a person who commits a serious crime condemned by the international community.]

Also read:War Crimes: Definition, Types, and Tribunals

Command responsibility requires the existence of certain circumstances, so that a commander of higher rank may be criminally liable, if he fails to prevent or punish criminal acts committed by his subordinates, while he has knowledge of such acts. Commanders have a heightened responsibility for law enforcement, such as in the customary laws of war.]

Also read:The Crime of Genocide in the Context of International Law

In conclusion, in international criminal law, two types of crimes are recognized, namely truly/core international crimes and other crimes or crimes against states. The concept of core international crimes has a major influence on the theory of state responsibility in ARSIWA, and state responsibility is given because there is a violation ofjus cogensand a violation oferga omnesobligations. But in addition, to eliminate impunity in international criminal law, there is individual criminal responsibility. In relation to this, the international community created an international criminal court, one of which is the ICC.

These are the answers we can provide, we hope you will find them useful.

